The north-south distinction refers to the socioeconomic division that exists between the economically developed, industrialized countries, collectively known as the north, and the low-income and middle-income countries, the south. Although north-south exchange or cooperation programs are common, the dynamics of north-south linkage have been traditionally described as unidirectional dependence, with growth in the south being determined primarily by developments in and priorities of the north. On the contrary, south-south cooperation refers to cooperative activities between newly industrialized southern countries and others in the south to find solutions to common development challenges including those related to health and health care. 1 For instance, health technology transfer has some unique characteristics, including discontinuous changes and multiplier effects, in that relatively low-tech or mid-level interventions such as immunization and drug treatment of selective conditions can have dramatic results in improvement of life expectancies initially. 2 Then a plateau 